  "description": [
    "The Poeahontas Times Entered at the postoffice at Marlin ton W Va as second class matter CALVIN W PRICE EDIIOR Thursday Octoher 23 1913 They say that the true test of whether you are a seasoned writer or not is the ability to bear up under typographical errors If you can see your linest sentence mutilated by an unseeing type setter and not become enraged it is a sign that you are an old hand at the business There is an ac count of a French author who died in a tit of angor caused by errors of this kind and also an Italian poet There is a case of a relig ious book of 172 pages of which 15 are taken up with errata T po graphical errors are not noticed so much except where they change the sublime into the ludicrous The author wrote no cross no crown and the typesetter got it no cows no cream His man ners would adorn a drawing room was changed into his man ners would alarm a drowning man The prohibitionist wrote that druDkeness is folly It appear ed Drunkeness is jolly An editor was trying to compliment a soldier by"
